<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Committee inquiry on _x000b_Food security</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">UK Food Group submission</span></p><p style="margin:9pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK Food Group welcomes the opportunity to make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> submission to the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Com</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mons Select Committee’s (EFRA) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nquiry on ‘food security’. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK Food Group is the main network of NGOs in the UK working on global food, agriculture and hunger issues, including development, environment, farmer, consumer and academic groups. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This submission is structured according to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">questions posed in the inquiry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s terms of reference</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s the first four of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> questions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some of the issues </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">raised in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the second set of four questions dealt with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> implicitly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Key points that we wish to highlight are:</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 45.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-45.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The impact of UK domest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ic food security policies and practices on international food security policies and practices, and vice versa, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of critical importance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to securing future food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> food system characterised by an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> industrial model of agriculture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, a global market in which a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">few companies hold concentrated market power</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">long unaccountable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> supply chain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is vulnerable to shocks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, damages the environment and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> can seriously reduce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the capacity of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> food </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">producers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> especially small-scale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> producers, to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provide healthy and delicious </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">food and achieve the right to food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 45.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-45.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">GM crops have not provided yield improvements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> do not provide any nutritional advantage that cannot better be realised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> biodiverse food production. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">They are promoted as a result of proprietary interests</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 45.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-45.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iodiverse and ecological </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">approaches</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of small-scale food providers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">adapted to local circumstances and control</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">led democratically</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, are more resilient to climate change and other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">economic and social pressures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> offers the potential for a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fairer food syste</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m that could eradicate hunge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r and restore the environment.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It would also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> safeguard the genetic basis for future </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plant breeding and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">adaptation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to a changing climate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 45.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-45.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uilding on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">successful </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">processes used in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> UN Committee on Wo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ld Food Security (CF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could strive to be more inclusive in its normative processes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> relating to food provision. It could invite</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">epresentatives of small-scale food producers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> networks, particularly those linked with La Ví</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a Campesina, the international peasant movement,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to participate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in UK decision making forums</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:36pt 0pt 9pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; letter-spacing:0.2pt">1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How best to improve UK (and EU) food security, including using resources </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">more efficiently</span></h1><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">National food security in the UK, as well as European food security can only be secured by achieving global food securit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Food security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should be measured in terms of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> availability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> affordability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, nutritional value</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the resilience and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sustainability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of these three over time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Governments, including the UK’s, have a legal obligation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the Right to Food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">progressively </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reach a point where food security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is achieved. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This includes ‘extraterritorial obligations’ to be aware of any impact of the UK’s national policies elsewhere in the world and to take action to prevent them causing any damage.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Policy approaches for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">achieving th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e Right to Food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Global networks</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and social movements of small-scale food producers, including farmers, pastoralists, fisherfolk and indigenous people, have defined their own </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">policy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vision for the food system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the framework of food sovereign</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty:</span></p><p style="margin:2pt 18pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“Food sovereignty is the right of peoples to healthy and culturally appropriate food produced through ecologically sound and sustainable methods, and their right to define their own food and agriculture systems. It puts the aspirations and needs of tho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se who produce, distribute and consume food at the heart of food systems and policies rather than the demands of markets and corporations.”</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The world already produces enough food to be able to feed everybody.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It is over a decade since the then UN Special </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rapporteur on the Right to Food, Jean Ziegler, noted that the world already produced enough food to feed 12 billion people,</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and food production has increased since then.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The problem is access to food and the means for its production.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Increasing productio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n, per se, will not alter levels of hunger, if those who are food insecure or are malnourished continue to be unable to afford adequate nutritious food: reducing poverty is the most effective way to improve food security. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One aspect of this is policies to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support the ability of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">small-scale farmers, in the UK as well as elsewhere in the world, to make decent living.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Support for biodiverse small</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scale and ecological producers is vital for UK and EU food security because genetic diversity is critical for resil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ience to pests and other challenges which are likely to get worse with climate change. The Irish potato famine was caused by Ireland’s dependence on very few varieties of potato – making the crop very susceptible to disease. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Indigenous and local plant vari</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the field continue to evolve and adapt to environmental change unlike those in gene banks, making them more resilient. Thus, centres of genetic diversity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">such as potatoes in the Andes,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are important for the UK and EU’s food security and economy.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Two </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK and EU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">policies that have damaging effects on food security are:</span></p><p style="margin:2pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-13.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">biofuels subsidies, which promote </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">production of non-food commodities and undermine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> food provision</span></p><p style="margin:2pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-13.5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">restrictive measures and technologies that reduce Farmers’ Rights to sow, use, exc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hange and sell their seeds</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some further drivers of food insecurity are discussed in more detail below.</span></p><h2 style="margin:24pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; letter-spacing:0.2pt">1.1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Efficient resource use</span></h2><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The majority of agricultural resources are not currently used to feed people, but instead are either used for animal feed, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agrofuels and other industrial commodities, or produce foods that are wasted. A redirection of these resources towards producing food for direct human consumption, in ways that are socially and environmentally sustainable would secure future food provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> both in the UK and internationally</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Modern intensive a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">griculture faces many environmental problems – soil degradation and erosion, water pollution and excess demand for irrigation, loss of agricultural biodiversity. In addition it faces social problems – l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oss of rural jobs and livelihoods and undermining of local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and traditional knowledge of ecosystem management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, sustainable agriculture and genetic resources for food and agriculture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In response to these food, equity and e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nvironmental challenges, the UN/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">World Bank-sponsored International Assessment of Agricultural Knowledge, Science and Technology for Development (IAASTD) recommended that:</span></p><p style="margin:2pt 18pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“An increase and strengthening of AKST [agricultural knowledge, science and technology] towards agroecological scienc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es will contribute to addressing environmental issues while maintaining and increasing productivity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">17</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Agroecology is explained by UN Special Rapporteur </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Right to Food, Olivier De Schutter as follows:</span></p><p style="margin:2pt 18pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“Agroecology is both a science and a set of pract</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ices. It was created by the convergence of two scientific disciplines: agronomy and ecology. As a science, agroecology is the “application of ecological science to the study, design and management </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of sustainable agroecosystems.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a set of agricultural pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">actices, agroecology seeks ways to enhance agricultural systems by mimicking natural processes, thus creating beneficial biological interactions and synergies among the components of the agroecosystem. It provides the most favourable soil conditions for pl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ant growth, particularly by managing organic matter and by raising soil biotic activity. The core principles of agroecology include recycling nutrients and energy on the farm, rather than introducing external inputs; integrating crops and livestock; divers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ifying species and genetic resources in agroecosystems over time and space; and focusing on interactions and productivity across the agricultural system, rather than focusing on individual species. Agroecology is highly knowledge-intensive, based on techni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ques that are not delivered top-down but developed on the basis of farmers’ knowledge and experimentation.”</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><h2 style="margin:24pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; letter-spacing:0.2pt">1.2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Agricultural Investment</span></h2><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">18</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Investment and support in strengthening </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and protecting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agroecological farming by small-scale food producers, in the framew</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ork of food sovereignty, has the most potential for supporting livelihoods and rural communities, reducing poverty, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensuring access to food for vulnerable groups, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">creating resilient food systems, enabling people to have a healthy diet and regenerating the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">environment. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This in turn is important for enhancing peace, stability and prosperity worldwide.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">19</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK Government, as a member of the CFS, is party to the negotiations for the principles for responsible agricultural investment in the context of food securi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty and nutrition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that are currently underway at the UN Committee on World Food Security (CFS)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The CFS is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> forum that brings together not only member states but also civil society, the private sector, research networks, other UN bodies and philanthrop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ic organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is the foremost international platform for work toward the elimination of hunger and ensuring food security and nutrition for everyone. The UK could provide increased support for developing investment principles in the CFS that will bu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ild on the investments made by small-scale food providers themselves both in the UK and internationally. </span></p><h2 style="margin:24pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; letter-spacing:0.2pt">1.3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Food waste</span></h2><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">20</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is important to recognize the role of food waste in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undermining</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> food security. Every step of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the food chain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has certain losses or waste </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">associated. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A small propo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of that waste is unavoidable and intrinsic to the product (e.g. non edible portions of fruit and vegetables), whereas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a much larger proportion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is avoidable and usually related to inefficient systems or market and cultural res</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">trictions. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Estimates suggest that between one third and one half of global food production is thrown away, wasting not only the food but also all the energy and resources that have gone into producing that food.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some of the major culprits of food waste are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> inadequate storage and transport infrastructure, irresponsible consumption (buying more than is needed) and restrictive selection rules (as in the case of fruits that are only accepted by retailers if the fit some predetermined aesthetic characteristics).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> An</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">other aspect of food waste that i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s usually not discussed is the one represented by the inefficiency of feeding human edible crops to animals instead</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of directly to people.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">21</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n eminently sensible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> measure that could both reduce waste and use existing resou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rces more efficiently has been put forward by the Pig Idea </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">policy campaign</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with their proposal to reintroduce the conversion of food waste into feed for pig production, using approved cooking processes that render it safe for use as feed by killing any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pathogens present such as foot and mouth disease and classical swine fever. DEFRA is encouraged to work with the Pig Idea and BPEX to implement this initiative, already common in other countries such as Japan, South Korea, China and many states in the USA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This would not only reduce the financial costs of meat production (animal feed costs have gone up markedly over recent years), but also greatly reduce the demand for very large amounts of soya and other crops for animal food, which in turn have enormous s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ocial and environmental impacts during production and processing – such as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> land dispossessions and conflicts, high levels of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> water and fertiliser use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd wide-spread forest clearance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> particularly in tropical ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eas.</span></p><h2 style="margin:24pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; letter-spacing:0.2pt">1.4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Trade</span></h2><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">22</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bilateral and international trade </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agreements can undermine food security. Excluding elements in the agreements and negotiations that impact on food provision is demanded by the social movements of the world’s food providers </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">23</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since the WTO's Agreement on Agriculture came into force in 1995,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> unequal powers are distorting food trade, and a few multinational agribusinesses have increased their domination of global input supply, trade and food distribution.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Conflict between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WTO rules and food security have been highlighted at the recent WTO Mini</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sterial in Bali, without resolution other than in a temporary ‘peace clause’.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> There are deep concerns about current EU trade negotiations with the USA and Canada. The possible Trans-Atlantic Trade Agreement risks undermining the UK’s (and EU’s) ability to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">control its own food system. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">24</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These negotiations should be fully transparent. As the Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy has emphasised, </span></p><p style="margin:2pt 18pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“the TTIP negotiations should result in an agreement that prohibits—rather than promotes—efforts by corporation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s to play off regulatory standards in one jurisdiction against the other. Those dialogues should hold open the possibility that the best avenues for progress could be outside the constraints of trade rules, as happened with the recent U.S.-EU agreement on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">organic standards. Proposals to broaden the definition of investment to apply to SPS and financial market regulations, making </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">them subject to challenge under investor-state dispute resolution, should be firmly rejected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:36pt 0pt 9pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; letter-spacing:0.2pt">2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The relationship between the pric</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e of fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">od and the cost of producing it</span></h1><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">25</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The relationship between the price of food and what farmers receive for producing it has become increasingly disconnected. In a trend that started at the end of the last century, most of the money spent on food purcha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ses goes to non-farmers. It is estimated that UK farmers receive only 9p of every £1 spent on food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">According to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DEFRA’s own figures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">farmers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> income</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fell</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">between 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2012.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Over this same period, the profits of the big</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">even</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> supermarkets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rose to £7.6bn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The market power of intermediaries enables them to influence both farm-gate and consumer prices to their benefit.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">26</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The relationship between price and production is also affected by:</span></p><p style="margin:4pt 0pt 0pt 45.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-45.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">27</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">global market which links local market prices to factors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> affecting prices in other parts of the world</span></p><p style="margin:4pt 0pt 0pt 45.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-45.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">28</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">link to oil prices through mechanisation, chemical inputs and biofuel production</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which is further complicated by fossil fuel subsidies</span></p><p style="margin:4pt 0pt 0pt 45.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-45.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">29</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">waste (see above)</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">30</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Quality food production, with enhanced incomes for farmers, could be encouraged with incentives for providing ecosystem services and for using agroecological approaches for localised food systems that provide multiple benefits for society. Facilitating dis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tribution of food through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">air</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rade and similar mechanisms to protect the prices paid and the working conditions of food producers, would further enhance incomes</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">31</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Simultaneously, consumer prices for industrially produced foods could better reflect the true</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> costs of production</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and also the costs of treating diet related ill health.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Methods for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> internalising the externalities of production and consumption </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> differential taxing for products and production systems with high negative impacts on health and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the environment, creating a disincentive. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he revenue generated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> could be used</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to subsidise foods with positive health and environmental impacts, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">such as UK-grown fruit and vegetables or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> healthy and sustainable school meals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:36pt 0pt 9pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; letter-spacing:0.2pt">3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The implications of volatility i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">n global food supply </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">and demand for UK food security</span></h1><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">32</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Locally resilient food systems, incorporating adequate stocks of foods, can mitigate food price volatility. In contrast, the global industrialised commodity regime can exacerbate volatility. It is contro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lled by a handful of corporations that dominate the development and marketing of inputs (agrochemicals, seed varieties and livestock genetics), commercialisation of products, transport, trade and retail. They may redirect investments towards agrofuels, cel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lulose production, livestock feed or other commodities as subsidy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">regimes change and market opportunities arise, affecting prices and volatility in the global supply of crops.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">33</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK food self-sufficiency has declined rapidly in the past two and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">half decades</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, from almost 80% in 1984 to the current 60%. Even locally produced food in the UK is highly dependent on imports for feed and fertilizer. Food insecurity in the world will impact the UK. The demand for land to produce crops for other uses presents a serio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">us risk to food security and greater vulnerability to shocks. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">34</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is now generally agreed that the EU biofuels targets and the use of land to produce crops to feed animals, to name a few, affect food prices and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">availab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ility. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rowing livestock feed for i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ndu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strial livestock production, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the service of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an unhealthy increase in meat and dairy production, has significant impacts on food price volatility and availability.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">35</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Speculation in commodity futures markets is creating volatile price movements that do not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reflect true changes in demand and supply. Position limits were used effectively in the US for most of the twentieth century to prevent market manipulation and excessive speculation, and are used on markets in Australia, Japan, Hong Kong, Singapore, China </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and South Africa today. They are transparent and give traders legal certainty. The introduction of position limits could be a reduction in the opportunity cost of excessive speculation, through the diversion of capital into genuine, productive investment. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On the issue of liquidity, the argument that position limits, if set too low, could damage liquidity for hedgers is redundant when current levels of financial speculation are so far above historic norms. The UK’s current self-regulatory approach has a trac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">k record of failure and creates conflicts of interest and a regulatory race-to-the-bottom.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">36</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Public procurement of food can be a tool to tackle both increasing levels of food poverty and lack of support for small-scale farmers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example over the past 15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> years Brazil has shifted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">public food procurement from an industriali</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed and centrali</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed system to a locali</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed farm system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, improving the quality of school meals while reducing the ecological footprint</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The EU Food Links project has developed an action pl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an for public procurement with environmental, social/health and economic indicators, which could inform UK policy.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:36pt 0pt 9pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; letter-spacing:0.2pt">4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he potential value and contribution of science and GM</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> technology to UK food security</span></h1><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">37</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">GM crops have not provided yield improvements, are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mainly developed for industrial commodity production, and facilitate increased concentration of power over agriculture by biotech corporations. They do not provide any nutritional advantage that cannot better be realised through diverse diets provided by b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iodiverse food production. They have no role in any part of the solution for a sustainable and equitable food system in the UK or elsewhere. With regard to biotechnological research and development, the Precautionary Principle / Approach should prevail.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">38</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">netically modifie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> crops are frequently put forward as an essential tool for securing food supply in the future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> However, despite four decades of development GM crops, only two GM traits, herbicide tolerance and insect resistance(Bt), in mainly soya, maiz</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e, oilseed rape and cotton account, for about 99% of the GM crops grown commercially, predominantly used for animal feed , agrofuels and fibre production.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">39</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Herbicide tolerance (HT) and insect resistance (IR) are relative simple traits to genetically enginee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r because they only code for additional novel proteins within the plant.  These are agronomic traits which produce some short-term savings for farmers until weeds and insects developed resistance to the herbicides and the Bt toxins. There is no evidence th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at the addition of these GM traits has improved crop yields as compared with non-GM varieties. Indeed a comparison of maize and oilseed rape yield in predominantly GM USA and predominantly non-GM EU showed that the former has lagged behind in terms of annu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al yield increment since th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e advent of commercial GM crops.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">40</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Metabolic changes, intended and unintended, in GM crops raise the possibility of harmful changes taking place which require detailed assessment during risk assessments before crops can be approve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d to enter the food/feed chain. In addition, the direct application of herbicides on GM HT crops will increase exposure to toxic residues in the end food/feed product.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">41</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">More complex traits such as genes to produce beta carotene (for instance in Golden Rice)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, drought tolerance, saline tolerance and nitrogen fixation have proved to be much more difficult to develop because they seek to alter the metabolism of crop plants in a way that may have unexpected consequences in other biochemical pathways of the receiv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing plants.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">42</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Golden Rice cannot deliver the required amounts of vitamin A to people of a nutrient poor diet. The low levels of fat and oil in diets of poor people will also limit the conversion efficiency into Vitamin A. In the case of GM nitrogen-fixing ce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reals, little progress has been made over the last three decades. To achieve this objective, both the plant and N fixing bacterium have to be genetically modified to form a symbiotic relationship. It is worth noting that during evolutionary history, grass/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cereal species have never naturally evolved nitrogen fixing. The reason for this may lie in the high energy requirement for fixing nitrogen from the atmosphere which would divert significant amounts of sugars in cereals away for other functions such as gra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in formation. The consequence may be lower yield</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">43</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The combination of advance traditional plant breeding techniques (such as marker assisted selection) and using agroecological approaches for the natural re-building of soil f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ertility using crops rotation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> N-fixing crops such as clover and beans, crop rotations and efficient cycling of plant nutrients from the waste stream offer a quicker, surer, more efficient and environmentally sounder way forward than GM in protected varieties of crops containing elit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e genes. Developing diverse varieties and populations, grown in crop/livestock mixed production will improve resilience and sustain yields in all conditions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as well as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> increas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> access to the diverse diets needed to prevent the malnutrition </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">products</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> such as Golden Rice are supposed to tackle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. These methods are included in agroecological approaches to food production.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">44</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A key part of successful agroecological approaches is formed by policies and practices that will sustain agricultural biodiversity. Thi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s is generated by and underpins agroecological production systems. Agricultural biodiversity comprises the diversity of seeds, plants, livestock breeds and fish and other aquatic organisms used for food and of the associated pollinators, pest predators and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> soil organisms. Agricultural biodiversity is the component of biodiversity that has been developed by and has co-evolved with people, and it underpins the food system and the wider economy, human health, the security of food supplies, and the viability of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the biosphere. It is therefore essential to regulate, transform or prohibit any systems, methods, processes or technologies, which might damage or restrict agricultural biodiversity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> its related ecosystem functions. In order to develop agricultural bio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">diversity, priority should be given to in situ conservation and development of domesticated species on-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">farm, on the range and in rivers, ponds and lakes, by small-scale food producers, respecting their Farmers’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Rights</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and related</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rights</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">45</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As mentioned abo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ve the IAASTD report recommended strengthening </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agricultural kn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owledge, science and technology</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> towards agroecological sciences</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The UK is a signatory to the IAASTD reports. The UK could set an example globally by redirecting its science efforts from providi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng research in support of industrial commodity production towards agroecological approaches that support localised food regimes</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">46</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is thus an imperative for the UK government to re-direct R&amp;D and UKAid funding towards agroecological research and develop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ment which is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">driven by the needs of farmers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and small scale producers, as expressed by their social movements. Only 1% of public agricultural investment on research is allocated to agro-ecological projects while GM projects receive 15% of the funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">espite the rhetoric, the BIS AgriTech strategy will do little to address this imbalance and help realise food security. Instead a swift reversal of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">government’s research investm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ents by the BBSRC, and Defra, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and DFID’s investment in the CGIAR and oth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er national, regional and international research activities is required, so that agroecological approaches, developed in the framework of food sovereignty, receive the majority of the funding. </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">47</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Similarly there is a need to ensure that the research outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> can be taken up by farmers through well-funded and well-designed public extension services both in the UK and other regions. The direct involvement of farmers in training other farmers in improved agroecological techniques is a proven means to achieve thi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s. </span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:36pt 0pt 9pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; letter-spacing:0.2pt">5)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Further information</span></h1><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">48</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A series of guiding questions to help determine whether an agricultural system, small-scale or large-scale, contributes to sustainable livelihoods has been outlined by some leading academic thinkers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Responding to tho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se questions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> context of the UK food system c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould be a useful exercise for the EFRA committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-27.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">49</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Should the EFRA committee require further information on the points raised, the UK Food Group would be pleased to provide this.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:2pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">La Vía Campesina, the international movement of peasants, small and medium scale farmers, has 150 member organizations in 70 countries from Africa, Asia, Europe and the Americas, and altogether represents about</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> 200 million farmers.</span></p><p style="margin:2pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Declaration of Nyéléni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Sélingué, Mali</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">, February 2007. </span><a href="http://www.nyeleni.org/IMG/pdf/DeclNyeleni-en.pdf"><span style="color:#008000; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">www.nyeleni.org/IMG/pdf/DeclNyeleni-en.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:2pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Commission on Human Rights, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">The right to food: report by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Special Rapporteur on the right to food, Mr. Jean Ziegler</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">E/CN.4/2001/53</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">. Geneva: UN, 2001, p2. </span><br /><a href="http://www.unhchr.ch/Huridocda/Huridoca.nsf/0/f45ea4df67ecca98c1256a0300340453/$FILE/G0111035.pdf"><span style="color:#008000; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">www.unhchr.ch/Huridocda/Huridoca.nsf/0/f45ea4df</span><span style="color:#008000; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">67ecca98c1256a0300340453/$FILE/G0111035.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:2pt 0pt 0pt 9pt; text-indent:-9pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">FAO, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">The state of food and agriculture 2010-11</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">. Rome: FAO, p73. </span><a href="http://www.fao.org/docrep/013/i2050e/i2050e.pdf"><span style="color:#008000; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; text-decoration:underline">www.fao.org/docrep/013/i2050e/i2050e.pdf</span></a><s